# Certificate Authority (CA)

An internal **Certificate Authority (CA)** was created within pfSense.

The CA issues certificates used by OpenVPN for certificate-based authentication.

Using an internal CA allows:

- Secure client authentication
- Certificate management
- Certificate revocation
- Encrypted VPN communications

![Certificate Authority](../Screenshots/07-Certificate-Authority.png)

---

# OpenVPN

OpenVPN provides encrypted remote access to the Enterprise Infrastructure Lab.

Configuration includes:

- UDP Transport
- Certificate-Based Authentication
- Dedicated VPN Tunnel
- Firewall Integration

Authenticated users can securely access internal lab resources from external networks.

---

# Secure Shell (SSH)

SSH was enabled to allow secure remote administration of the pfSense firewall.

Administrative access is encrypted and can be used for:

- System maintenance
- Advanced troubleshooting
- Command-line administration

---

# Proxy Services

## Squid Proxy

Squid was deployed as the laboratory's forward proxy server.

Main functions include:

- HTTP/HTTPS proxy services
- Web caching
- Traffic optimization
- Centralized Internet access

---

## SquidGuard

SquidGuard extends Squid by providing web filtering capabilities.

It allows:

- URL filtering
- Category-based website blocking
- Content access policies
- Internet usage control

---

# Intrusion Detection and Prevention

## Snort IDS/IPS

Snort was installed as the network Intrusion Detection and Prevention System.

Its role within the laboratory is to:

- Detect malicious traffic
- Identify known attack signatures
- Generate security alerts
- Block malicious connections (IPS mode)

Snort will later be integrated with the Wazuh SIEM platform to demonstrate centralized security monitoring and attack detection.

---

# Services

The primary security services implemented in pfSense include:

- Stateful Firewall
- NAT
- OpenVPN
- Certificate Authority
- Squid Proxy
- SquidGuard
- Snort IDS/IPS

Core infrastructure services such as **DNS**, **DHCP**, **Active Directory**, and **Group Policy** are intentionally provided by the Windows Server to simulate a real enterprise environment.

